  "prompt": "What is the difference between fats and oils?",
  "response": "Fats and oils are both types of lipids, which are organic compounds that are insoluble in water but soluble in organic solvents. The main difference between fats and oils lies in their physical state at room temperature.\n\nFats are typically solid at room temperature, while oils are liquid. This difference in physical state is due to the types of fatty acids that make up the fats and oils. Fatty acids are long chains of carbon and hydrogen atoms with a carboxyl group at one end. \n\nSaturated fatty acids have single bonds between all of their carbon atoms and are straight, allowing them to pack closely together and form solids at room temperature. Unsaturated fatty acids have one or more double bonds between their carbon atoms, causing kinks in the chain that prevent them from packing closely together, resulting in a liquid state at room temperature.\n\nAnimal fats, such as lard and butter, are generally high in saturated fatty acids and are solid at room temperature. Plant oils, such as olive oil and sunflower oil, are generally high in unsaturated fatty acids and are liquid at room temperature. However, there are exceptions, such as coconut oil, which is high in saturated fatty acids and is solid at room temperature.",
